result.execSummary:
The defendant Jerome T Davis was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Unlawful Phone Use-Threatens Harm [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Habitual Criminality], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.012(1)(a).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Habitual Criminality], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

AS TO COUNT 2
The court sentenced the defendant to 316 DAYS in the House of Correction, consecutive to Count 3, with credit for 316 DAYS time served, this is a TIME SERVED DISPOSITION. Defendant Jerome T Davis in court with attorney Kiley Zellner.  Defendant Jerome T Davis in custody.  Owen M. Piotrowski appeared for the State of Wisconsin. 
AS TO COUNT 1
Pursuant to plea negotiations, on a motion of the state the court ordered Count 1 Dismissed, But Read In.
AS TO COUNTS 2 & 3
Defendant changes plea(s) to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea(s).  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Court advised that under 48 USC Section 922(g)(9) the defendant is prohibited from possession of a firearm and/or ammunition after conviction of a misdemeanor crime of domestic violence.
